The active components of Ginkgo biloba, namely ginkgolides and bilobalides, have been shown to inhibit platelet aggregation. However, the mechanism by which Ginkgo biloba causes haemorrhage when coadministered with other antiplatelet agents is not fully understood.

Some studies suggest that the synergistic effect of Ginkgo biloba and other antiplatelet agents may lead to an excessive inhibition of platelet function, resulting in an increased risk of bleeding. Other possible mechanisms include an interaction between the active components of Ginkgo biloba and the active components of the other antiplatelet agents, or an increased sensitivity of platelets to the inhibitory effects of Ginkgo biloba in the presence of other antiplatelet agents.

It is important for healthcare professionals to be aware of the potential risks of coadministering Ginkgo biloba with other antiplatelet agents, and to carefully consider the benefits and risks of such combinations in individual patients.

